# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: abn-amro
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] Following aggressive international expansion, ABN AMRO was acquired and broken up in 2007–2008 by a consortium of European banks, including Fortis which intended to take over its formed operations in the Benelux region.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] Fortis came under stress in the autumn of 2008, and was in turn broken up into separate national entities; the Dutch operations, namely Fortis Bank Nederland and the former ABN AMRO activities that Fortis had planned to absorb, were nationalized, restructured, and renamed ABN AMRO in mid-2010.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] On 20 November 2015, the Dutch government publicly re-listed the company through an IPO and sold 20 percent of the shares to the public.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] ABN AMRO has been designated as a Significant Institution since the entry into force of European Banking Supervision in late 2014, and as a consequence is directly supervised by the European Central Bank.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] In 1824, King William I established the Nederlandsche Handel-Maatschappij (NHM) a trading company to revive trade and financing of the Dutch East Indies and it would become one of the primary ancestors of ABN AMRO.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] The NHM merged with the *Twentsche Bank* in 1964, to form Algemene Bank Nederland (ABN).
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] Also in 1964, the *Amsterdamsche Bank*, established in 1871, merged with the *Rotterdamsche Bank*, established in 1873 (as part of a merger that included *Determeijer Weslingh & Zn.* from 1765), to form Amsterdamsche en Rotterdamsche Bank, known as AMRO Bank.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] On 22 September 1991, ABN and AMRO merged to form ABN AMRO.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] In 1993, two of its investment banking subsidiaries ― Bank Mees & Hope and Pierson, Heldring & Pierson ― merged in turn to form MeesPierson.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] The two merged banks brought to ABN AMRO a large network of overseas companies and branches.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] From NHM, ABN owned a significant branch network in Asia and the Middle East, including the Saudi Hollandi Bank owned by the NHM Jeddah branch.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] Another, the Hollandsche Bank-Unie (HBU), which grew from the merger of the *Hollandsche Bank voor de Middellandsche Zee* (HBMZ) and the *Hollandsche Zuid-Amerika Bank* in 1933, gave ABN AMRO an extensive network of branches in South and Central America.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] In 1979, ABN had expanded into North America with the acquisition of Chicago-based LaSalle National Bank.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] In 2005, Standard Federal became *LaSalle Bank Midwest* to unite ABN AMRO's two banking networks in the U.S.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] In 1995, ABN AMRO purchased The Chicago Corporation, an American securities and commodities trading and clearing corporation.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] Other major acquisitions included the Brazilian bank Banco Real in 1998, and the Italian bank Antonveneta in 2006.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] It was also involved in the controversial acquisition of the Dutch local government mortgage and building development organisation, the Bouwfonds in 2000.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] ABN AMRO sold the Bouwfonds as a going concern in 2006.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] In July 2006, Favonius Ventures, which was founded and headed by Roel Pieper, received all of the technology investments of ABN AMRO Capital which is the private equity business unit of ABN AMRO Bank N.V.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] ABN AMRO had come to a crossroads in early 2005.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] The bank had still not come close to its own target of having a return on equity that would put it among the top five of its peer group, a target that the CEO, Rijkman Groenink had set upon his appointment in 2000.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] From 2000 until 2005, ABN AMRO's stock price stagnated.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] Financial results in 2006 added to concerns about the bank's future.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] Operating expenses increased at a greater rate than operating revenue, and the efficiency ratio deteriorated further to 69.9%.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] Non-performing loans increased considerably year on year by 192%.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] Net profits were only boosted by sustained asset sales.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] In 2006, research findings were publicly released regarding ABN AMRO Bank N.V.'s predecessors and connections to African slavery.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] An examination of 200 predecessors of ABN AMRO Bank N.V. founded before 1888 determined that some had connections to African slavery, either in the United States or elsewhere in the Americas.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] By 2007, ABN AMRO was the second-largest bank in the Netherlands and the eighth-largest in Europe by assets.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] At that time, the magazine *The Banker* and Fortune Global 500 placed it 15th in the list of world's biggest banks and it had operations in 63 countries, with over 110,000 employees.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] Pakistan merged with Prime Commercial Bank which consisted of 69 branches across 24 cities.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] ABN AMRO Bank (Pakistan) Limited (Which later got merged into Royal Bank of Scotland Pakistan) was formed as the result of the US$227 million acquisition.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] On 21 February 2007, The Children's Investment Fund Management (TCI) hedge fund called to ask the Chairman of the Supervisory Board to actively investigate a merger, acquisition, or breakup of ABN AMRO, stating that the current stock price did not reflect the true value of the underlying assets.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] TCI asked the chairman to put its request on the agenda of the annual shareholders' meeting to be held in April 2007.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] Events accelerated on 20 March 2007, when the British bank Barclays and ABN AMRO both confirmed they were in exclusive talks about a possible merger.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] On 28 March 2007, ABN AMRO published the agenda for the shareholders' meeting of 2007.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] It included all items requested by TCI, but with the recommendation not to follow the request for a breakup of the company.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] According to the proposed deal, RBS would receive ABN's United States operations, LaSalle, and ABN's wholesale operations; Banco Santander would take the Brazilian operations; and Fortis, the Dutch operations.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] The three banks set up a joint venture, RFS Holdings (with a name based on their respective initials), to execute the transaction.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] On 23 April, ABN AMRO and Barclays announced the proposed acquisition of ABN AMRO by Barclays.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] The deal was valued at €67 billion and included the sale of LaSalle Bank to Bank of America for €21 billion.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] Two days later, the RBS-led consortium brought out its indicative offer, worth €72 billion, if ABN AMRO would abandon its sale of LaSalle Bank to Bank of America.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] During the shareholders' meeting the next day, approximately 68 percent of the shareholders voted in favor of the breakup as requested by TCI.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] The sale of LaSalle was seen as obstructive by many: as a way of blocking the RBS bid, which hinged on further access to the US markets, in order to expand on the success of the group's existing American brands, Citizens Bank and Charter One.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] On 3 May 2007, the Dutch Investors' Association (Vereniging van Effectenbezitters), with the support of shareholders representing up to 20 percent of ABN's shares, took its case to the Dutch commercial court in Amsterdam, seeking an injunction against the LaSalle sale.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] The court ruled that the sale of LaSalle could not be viewed apart from the current merger talks of Barclays with ABN AMRO and that the ABN AMRO shareholders should be able to approve other possible merger/acquisition candidates in a general shareholder meeting.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] However, in July 2007, the Dutch Supreme Court ruled that Bank of America's acquisition of LaSalle Bank could proceed and Bank of America absorbed LaSalle effective 1 October 2007.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] On 23 July 2007, Barclays raised its offer for ABN AMRO to €67.5bn, after securing investments from the governments of China and Singapore, but it was still short of the RBS consortium's offer.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] Barclay's revised bid was worth €35.73 a share — 4.3% more than its previous offer.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] The offer, which included 37% cash, remained below the €38.40-a-share offer made the week before by the RFS consortium.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] The revised offer did not include an offer for La Salle Bank since ABN AMRO could proceed with the sale of that subsidiary to Bank of America.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] RBS would now settle for ABN's investment-banking division and its Asian Network.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] On 30 July 2007, ABN AMRO withdrew its support for Barclays' offer which was lower than the offer from the group led by RBS.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] While the Barclays offer matched ABN AMRO's "strategic vision," the board couldn't recommend it from "a financial point of view." The US$98.3bn bid from RBS, Fortis, and Banco Santander was 9.8% higher than Barclays' offer.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] Barclays Bank withdrew its bid for ABN AMRO on 5 October, clearing the way for the RBS-led consortium's bid to go through, along with its planned dismemberment of ABN AMRO.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] RFS formally acquired ABN AMRO on 17 October 2007.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] Fortis would receive ABN AMRO's Dutch and Belgian operations, Banco Santander would get Banco Real in Brazil, and Banca Antonveneta in Italy and RBS would get ABN AMRO's wholesale division and all other operations, including those in Asia.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] Both RBS and Fortis were increasingly visibly overextended following the ABN AMRO acquisition.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] On 22 April 2008, RBS announced the largest rights issue in British corporate history, which aimed to raise £12billion in new capital to offset a writedown of £5.9billion resulting from the bad investments and to shore up its reserves following the purchase of ABN AMRO.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] On 11 July 2008, Fortis CEO Jean Votron stepped down after the ABN AMRO deal had depleted Fortis's capital.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] The total worth of Fortis, as reflected by its stock value, was at that time one-third of what it had been before the acquisition, and just under the value it had paid for the Benelux activities of ABN AMRO.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] On 3 October 2008, Fortis was nationalised.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] The Dutch government bought a number of Fortis divisions plus Fortis's share in ABN AMRO for EUR 16.8 billion.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] It subsequently announced that the parts of ABN AMRO it had acquired would be integrated with Fortis Bank Nederland (FBN) to create a new ABN AMRO.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] On 13 October 2008, British Prime Minister Gordon Brown announced a UK government bailout of the financial system.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] The Treasury would infuse £37 billion ($64 billion, €47 billion) of new capital into Royal Bank of Scotland Group Plc, Lloyds TSB and HBOS Plc, to avert financial sector collapse.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] This resulted in a total government ownership in RBS of 58%.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] As a consequence of this rescue, the chief executive of the group Fred Goodwin offered his resignation, which was duly accepted.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] Later in October, Fortis announced that it would sell its stake in RFS Holdings, which included all activities that had not been transferred yet to Fortis (i.e. everything except asset management).
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] In September 2009, RBS rebranded the Morgans sharedealing business in Australia as RBS Morgans.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] This followed the rebranding of the ABN AMRO Australia unit to RBS Australia in March that year.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] On 10 February 2010, RBS announced that branches it owned in India and the United Arab Emirates were to be rebranded under its name.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] HSBC Holdings said it would buy the Indian retail and commercial banking businesses of Royal Bank of Scotland for $1.8bn, however the deal fell-through in December 2012.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] The operations owned by Santander, notably those in Italy and Brazil, were merged with Santander, sold or eliminated.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] The Dutch government had obtained full control of all Fortis operations in the Netherlands, including those parts of ABN-AMRO then belonging to Fortis, at a price of €16.8bn.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] The government and the De Nederlandsche Bank president have announced the merger of Dutch Fortis and ABN AMRO parts will proceed while the bank is in state ownership.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] This was completed in July 2010, when Fortis operations in the Netherlands were rebranded ABN AMRO.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] In November 2008, a Belgian court dismissed a suit by shareholders of Fortis objecting to the Belgian government's handling of the Fortis/ABN AMRO transaction and subsequent break-up.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] The Dutch government appointed former Dutch finance minister Gerrit Zalm as CEO to restructure and stabilise the bank, and in February 2010 the assets it owned were legally demerged from those owned by RBS.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] This demerger created two separate organisations, ABN AMRO Bank N.V. and The Royal Bank of Scotland N.V.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] The former was merged with ABN AMRO Private Banking, Fortis Bank Nederland, the private bank MeesPierson (formerly owned by the original ABN AMRO and Fortis) and the diamond bank International Diamond & Jewelry Group to create ABN AMRO Group N.V., with the Fortis name being dropped on 1 July 2010.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] The remaining parts of the original ABN AMRO still owned by The Royal Bank of Scotland N.V., meanwhile, were renamed, sold or closed.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] As part of the agreement with the European Commission on state aid in the restructuring, ABN AMRO sold Hollandsche Bank-Unie to Deutsche Bank in April 2010, together with another subsidiary, IFN Finance.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] ABN AMRO acquired the specialist on-line mortgage provider *Direktbank Hypotheken* as part of the nationalisation and from 1 January 2011, it stopped selling these products under this brand to the public.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] It absorbed the mortgage business into its own products under the ABN AMRO brand as well as Florius brand.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] In November 2020, ABN AMRO announced it would cut 2800 jobs and sell its head offices as a plan to reduce costs, hoping to save €700 million by 2024.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] In December 2023, ABN AMRO acquired BUX to boost its digital presence for an undisclosed amount.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] In May 2024, ABN AMRO agreed to buy Hauck Aufhäuser Lampe (HAL), a German private bank specialised in wealth management, for 672 million euros ($730 million) from Chinese conglomerate Fosun International.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] In October 2024, the Dutch government announced its plan to reduce its stake in ABN AMRO from 40.5% to 30% in the coming months.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] On 12 November 2025, ABN AMRO announced the acquisition of Dutch lender NIBC Bank for 960 million euros from American private equity firm Blackstone.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] ABN AMRO Bank has offices in 15 countries with 32,000 employees, most of whom are based in the Netherlands with only 5,000 in other countries.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] Its operations include a private banking division which focuses on high-net-worth clients in 14 countries as well as commercial and merchant banking operations that play a major role in energy, commodities and transportation markets as well as brokerage, clearing, and custody.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] In April 2022, ABN AMRO Bank announced the company had signed a multi-year subscription extension with Switzerland based Banking and financial software development organisation Temenos.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] The deal was made to support ABN AMRO with customer growth and overall business expansion on the Temenos Banking cloud.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] The bank refers to itself as ABN AMRO in all capitals, based on an acronym of the two originating banks names Algemene Bank Nederland and the Amsterdam and Rotterdam Bank, in the second case the first two letters of each city make up the word AMRO.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] The letters in 'ABN' are pronounced separately and 'AMRO' is pronounced as a word.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] For this reason some media spell the name as 'ABN Amro'.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] In written text both versions are used, although the bank itself uses only the uppercase version.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] In conversations, the bank is sometimes referred to as simply ABN or AMRO bank depending on one's location around the world.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] The green and yellow shield logo was designed by Landor Associates for ABN AMRO in 1991, and has been used as a brand for the bank and all its subsidiaries.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] ABN AMRO was the main sponsor of Dutch football club AFC Ajax of Amsterdam from 1991 to 2008.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] The sponsor logo was at the time the only one in the world to be printed vertically down the right hand side of the front of the shirt.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] As of 2014, ABN AMRO is one of the strategic industry partners with Duisenberg School of Finance.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] The bank's former art collection has been managed since the end of 2007 by a dedicated foundation, the Stichting ABN AMRO Kunstverzameling.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] As a result of the alleged fraud by Bernard Madoff, Fortis Bank Netherlands (Holding) NV lost 1 billion euros on loans from the bank (through its subsidiary Prime Fund Solutions, part of Fortis Merchant Banking) to hedge fund and as collateral investments in Bernard Madoff Investment Securities.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] The Dutch government said on behalf of Fortis that a claim against the Securities and Exchange Commission would be considered.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] ABN AMRO was mentioned by the United States Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) in court filings when it sued Goldman Sachs and one of Goldman's collateralized debt obligation (CDO) traders on 16 April 2010.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] The SEC alleges that Goldman defrauded both IKB Deutsche Industriebank and ABN AMRO by its failure to disclose that the CDOs it sold to both banks were not assembled by a third party, but instead through the guidance of a hedge fund that was counterparty in the CDS transaction.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] This hedge fund, Paulson & Co., stood to reap great financial benefit in the event of default.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] ABN AMRO bank is one of the main banks financing the diamond business.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] ABN AMRO had branches in Botswana, New York, Hong Kong, Mumbai and Dubai, all of which they have sold or are in process of closing.
[src:abn-amro/aac-capital-partners] They currently only have a branch in Antwerp, where they are also shrinking their business.
[src:abn-amro/aex-index] The **AEX index**, derived from **Amsterdam Exchange index**, is a stock market index composed of Dutch companies that trade on Euronext Amsterdam, formerly known as the *Amsterdam Stock Exchange*.
[src:abn-amro/aex-index] Started in 1983, the index is composed of a maximum of 30 of the most frequently traded securities on the exchange.
[src:abn-amro/aex-index] It is one of the main national indices of the stock exchange group Euronext alongside Euronext Brussels' BEL20, Euronext Dublin's ISEQ 20, Euronext Lisbon's PSI-20, the Oslo Bors OBX Index, and Euronext Paris's CAC 40.
[src:abn-amro/aex-index] The AEX started from a base level of 100 index points on 3 January 1983 (a corresponding value of 45.378 is used for historic comparisons due to the adoption of the Euro).
[src:abn-amro/aex-index] The index's peak to date was set on 26 October 2021 816.91 After the dot-com bubble in 1999, the index value more than halved over the following three years before recovering in line with most global financial markets.
[src:abn-amro/aex-index] The AEX index dealt with its second largest one-day loss on 12 March 2020, when the index closed down almost 11% during the coronavirus pandemic.
[src:abn-amro/aex-index] The AEX index enjoyed its third largest one-day loss on 29 September 2008, when the index closed down almost 9%.
[src:abn-amro/aex-index] The decade between 1998 and 2008 was bad for the AEX index, as it was the worst performing stock index except for the OMX Iceland 15.
[src:abn-amro/aex-index] The preceding years were a lot better compared to the rest of the world.
[src:abn-amro/aex-index] The following table shows the annual development of the AEX index since 1983.
[src:abn-amro/aex-index] As of 2011, the AEX index composition is reviewed four times a year - a full "annual" review in March and interim "quarterly" reviews in June, September and December.
[src:abn-amro/aex-index] Any changes made as a result of the reviews take effect on the third Friday of the month.
[src:abn-amro/aex-index] Previously reviews were held in March and September only.
[src:abn-amro/aex-index] Prior to 2008, index changes were made only annually in March.
[src:abn-amro/aex-index] At the main March review date, the 23 companies listed on Euronext Amsterdam's regulated market with the highest share turnover (in Euros) over the previous year are admitted to the index.
[src:abn-amro/aex-index] Of the companies ranked between 24th and 27th, a further two are selected with preference given to existing constituents of the index.
[src:abn-amro/aex-index] Companies which have fewer than 25% of shares considered free float on Euronext Amsterdam are, however, ineligible for inclusion.
[src:abn-amro/aex-index] Unlike some other European benchmark equity indices (such as the OMXS30), if a company has more than one class of shares traded on the exchange, only the most frequently traded of these will be accepted into the AEX.
[src:abn-amro/aex-index] If a company or companies are removed from the index due to delisting, acquisition or another reason, no replacements are made until the next review date.
[src:abn-amro/aex-index] At the three interim reviews in June, September and December, no changes are made to the AEX unless either the index has seen one or more constituents removed, or a non-constituent possesses a share turnover ranked 15th or higher overall over the previous 12 months.
[src:abn-amro/aex-index] If vacancies are to be filled, the highest-ranking non-AEX companies are selected to join the index.
[src:abn-amro/aex-index] The AEX is a capitalization-weighted index.
[src:abn-amro/aex-index] At each main annual review, the index weightings of companies in the index are capped at 15%, but range freely with share price subsequently.
[src:abn-amro/aex-index] The index weights are calculated with respect to the closing prices of the relevant companies on 1 March.
[src:abn-amro/aex-index] At the interim reviews, weightings after adjustment are left as close as possible to those of the previous day and are not re-capped.
[src:abn-amro/aex-index] The index comprises a basket of shares, the numbers of which are based on the constituent weights and index value at the time of readjustment.
[src:abn-amro/aex-index] The AEX Index is traded as a future on the Euronext Equities & Index Derivatives exchange (EUREID) under the ticker symbol FTI.
[src:abn-amro/aex-index] The size of each contract is 200 EURO x AEX Index points (e.g.
[src:abn-amro/aex-index] The index is composed of the following listings as of 31 December 2024.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax was one of the most successful clubs in the world in the 20th century.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] According to the International Federation of Football History & Statistics, Ajax was the seventh-most successful European club of the 20th century and *The World's Club Team of the Year* in 1992.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] According to German magazine *Kicker*, Ajax was the second-most successful European club of the 20th century.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The club is one of five teams that have earned the right to keep the European Cup and to wear a multiple-winner badge.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] In 1972, they completed the continental treble by winning the Eredivisie, KNVB Cup, and the European Cup.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] They also won the first (albeit unofficial) European Super Cup against Rangers in January 1973.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax's most recent international trophies are the 1995 Intercontinental Cup, 1995 UEFA Super Cup and the 1995 Champions League, where they defeated Milan in the final; they lost the 1996 Champions League final on penalties to Juventus.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] In 1995, Ajax was crowned as *World Team of the Year* by *World Soccer* magazine.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax is also one of four teams to win the continental treble and the Intercontinental Cup or Club World Cup in the same season/calendar year; this was achieved in the 1971–72 season.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax is one of five clubs to have won all three major UEFA club competitions played until 2021.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] They have also won the Intercontinental Cup twice, the 1991–92 UEFA Cup, as well as the Karl Rappan Cup, a predecessor of the UEFA Intertoto Cup in 1962.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax plays at the Johan Cruyff Arena, which opened as the Amsterdam ArenA in 1996 and was renamed in 2018.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] They previously played at De Meer Stadion and the Amsterdam Olympic Stadium (for international matches).
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Throughout their history, Ajax have cultivated a reputation for scouting, spotting and developing young talent, and have remained focused on developing a youth system.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax was founded in Amsterdam on 18 March 1900.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The club achieved promotion to the highest level of Dutch football in 1911 and had its first major success in 1917, winning the KNVB Beker, the Netherlands' national cup.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The following season, Ajax became national champion for the first time.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The club defended its title in 1918–19, becoming the only team to achieve an unbeaten season in the Netherlands Football League Championship.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Throughout the 1920s, Ajax was a strong regional power, winning the Eerste Klasse West division in 1921, 1927 and 1928, but could not maintain its success at the national level.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] This changed in the 1930s, with the club winning five national championships (1931, 1932, 1934, 1937, 1939), making it the most successful Dutch team of the decade.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax won its second KNVB Cup in 1942–43, and an eighth Dutch title in 1946–47, the last season the club was managed by Englishman Jack Reynolds, who, up to this point, had overseen all of its national championship successes as well as its 1917 KNVB Cup win.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] In 1956, the first season of the Netherlands' new professional league, the Eredivisie, was played with Ajax participating as a founding member.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The Amsterdam club became the first national champions under the new format and made its debut in the European Champion Clubs' Cup the following year, losing to Hungarian champions Vasas SC 6–2 on aggregate at the quarter-final stage.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The team was again Eredivisie champions in 1960 and won a third KNVB Cup in 1961.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] In 1965, Rinus Michels, who had played for the club between 1946 and 1958, was appointed manager of Ajax, implementing his philosophy of Total Football which was to become synonymous with both Ajax and the Netherlands national team.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] A year earlier, Johan Cruyff, who would go on to become widely regarded as the greatest Dutch footballer of all time, made his debut.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Between them, Michels and Cruyff led Ajax through the most successful period in its history, winning seven Eredivisie titles, four KNVB Cups and three European Cups.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax won the Dutch championship in 1966, 1967 and 1968, and reached the 1969 European Cup final, losing to Milan.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] During the 1966–67 season, Ajax scored a record 122 goals in an Eredivisie season and also won the KNVB Cup to achieve its first league and cup double.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] In 1969–70, Ajax won a fourth Dutch league championship and second league and cup double in five seasons, winning 27 out of 34 league matches and scoring 100 goals.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The 1970–71 season saw Ajax retain the KNVB Cup and reach the 1971 European Cup final, where they defeated Panathinaikos 2–0 with goals from Dick van Dijk and Arie Haan to become continental champions for the first time, with Cruyff being named European Footballer of the Year.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] After this success, Michels departed to become manager of Barcelona and was replaced by the Romanian Ștefan Kovács.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] In Kovács' first season, Ajax completed a treble of the European Cup, the Eredivisie and a third consecutive KNVB Cup.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The following season, the team beat Argentine Club Atlético Independiente to win the 1972 Intercontinental Cup and retained their Eredivisie and European Cup titles, becoming the first club to win three consecutive European Cups since Real Madrid in the 1950s.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] In 1973, Michels' Barcelona broke the world transfer record to bring Cruyff to the Catalan team.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Kovács also departed to become manager of the France national team, signalling the end of this period of international success.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] In 1976–77, Ajax won its first domestic championship in four seasons and recorded a double of the Eredivisie and KNVB Cup two years later.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The early 1980s saw the return of Cruyff to the club, as well as the emergence of young players Marco van Basten and Frank Rijkaard.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The team won back-to-back Eredivisie titles in 1982 and 1983, with all three playing a significant role in the latter.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] After Cruyff's sale to rivals Feyenoord in 1983, van Basten became Ajax's key player, top scoring in the Eredivisie for four seasons between 1983–84 and 1986–87.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] In 1985, Cruyff returned to Ajax as manager and the team ended his first season in charge with 120 goals from 34 matches.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] However, Ajax still finished as runner-up to PSV by eight points.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The following season, Ajax again lost out on the Eredivisie title to PSV, but won the European Cup Winners' Cup, its first continental trophy in 14 years.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] After this, Cruyff left the club to become manager of Barcelona and Rijkaard and van Basten were sold to Sporting CP and Milan respectively.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Despite these losses, Ajax reached a second consecutive Cup Winners' Cup final in 1988, where they lost to Belgian club KV Mechelen.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The 1988–89 season saw Dennis Bergkamp, a young forward who had first appeared under Cruyff in 1986, establish himself as a regular goalscorer for Ajax.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Bergkamp helped Ajax to the Eredivisie title and was the top scorer in the division in 1990–91, 1991–92 and 1992–93.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Under the management of Louis van Gaal, Ajax won the UEFA Cup in 1992 to become the second club, after Juventus, to have won all three major European club competitions.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The team regained the Dutch championship in 1993–94, and won it again in 1994–95 and 1995–96 to become the first Ajax side to win three back-to-back championships since 1968.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The height of van Gaal's success came in 1994–95, where Ajax became the first, and to date only, team to complete an entire Eredivisie season unbeaten.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The team also won its first European Cup since its 1970s era, defeating Milan in the 1995 UEFA Champions League final 1–0, with the winning goal scored by 18-year-old Patrick Kluivert.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax again reached the final one year later, and was defeated on penalties by Juventus.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax's return as a European force was short-lived, as van Gaal and several members of the squad soon departed to some of the continent's biggest clubs.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The 2000s was a lean decade for the club, with only two Eredivisie championships won.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] However, Ajax's academy continued to produce star players such as Wesley Sneijder and Rafael van der Vaart.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] In 2010, Frank de Boer was appointed manager of Ajax and led the club to its first league title in seven years, and record 30th title overall, in the 2010–11 season.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] This was followed by back-to-back wins in 2011–12 and 2012–13 to match his three consecutive titles as a player in the 1990s.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] In 2013–14, Ajax was again Eredivisie champions, winning four consecutive league titles for the first time in club history.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] After finishing as runner-up to PSV in both 2014–15 and 2015–16, de Boer resigned as Ajax head coach in May 2016.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Peter Bosz took over the club and led them to the 2017 UEFA Europa League final, their first European final in 21 years.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] They lost to Manchester United with a lineup that was the youngest ever in a European final, averaging an age of 22 years and 282 days.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] For the third consecutive season, they finished runner-up in the Eredivisie, this time to Feyenoord.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The 2018–19 season for Ajax involved a remarkable run in the UEFA Champions League.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Due to their runner-up finish in the 2017–18 Eredivisie, Ajax entered the tournament in the second qualifying round.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] After successive victories against Sturm Graz, Standard Liège and Dynamo Kyiv, they qualified for the group stage.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax was drawn in a group with German champions Bayern Munich, Portuguese side Benfica and Greek champions AEK Athens.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax finished runner-up in this group, qualifying for the knockout stages, where it was drawn against three-time defending champions Real Madrid.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] After losing 1–2 in the first leg, they defeated Real Madrid 4–1 in the away match, stunning the defending champions in their own stadium, the Santiago Bernabéu, with an aggregate score of 5–3.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Dušan Tadić was awarded a perfect score of 10 by *L'Équipe* following the match.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Thus, Ajax progressed to the quarter-finals and was drawn with Italian champions Juventus.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] In the first leg in the Johan Cruyff Arena, they drew 1–1.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] In the second leg at the Juventus Stadium, Ajax came from behind to win 2–1 and 3–2 on aggregate.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Matthijs de Ligt scored the winning goal for Ajax to help the team advance to its first Champions League semi-final since 1997.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] There, they would face English side Tottenham Hotspur.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] In the first leg of the semi-final, Ajax beat Tottenham 1–0 away from home.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] In the second leg, Ajax scored twice in the first half to generate a 3–0 lead on aggregate.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] However, in the second half, Lucas Moura scored three times, including in the 6th minute of added time, resulting in Ajax losing via the away goals rule.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax was in first place on goal difference when the Eredivisie was declared void, preventing them being Dutch champions for the 35th time, but still qualified for the 2020–21 UEFA Champions League.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] In this, it was eliminated again, but in 2021 it reached the quarter-finals of the Europa League.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] That season, it again won both the national title and the KNVB Cup.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] In the 2021-22 season, Ajax again became champion of the Netherlands.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] It had to give up the KNVB Cup and the Johan Cruijff Shield to competitor PSV because it came out on the losing end in both finals.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] In European terms, Ajax achieved first place in the Champions League group, all six matches were won, mostly by a wide margin.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] After the winter break, Ajax was narrowly eliminated in the eighth finals by the Portuguese Benfica Lisboa (Lisbon) (2–2 away, 0–1 at home).
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] As of 1 July 2022, Alfred Schreuder succeeded Erik ten Hag, who left for Manchester United, as Ajax's coach.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Most of the key players from previous seasons left during the summer transfer period, but there was also a lot of reinvestment.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax started the 2022/23 season relatively well with six consecutive victories in the Eredivisie.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] But Ajax was eliminated from the Champions League quite quickly in a group with Liverpool, Napoli and Rangers.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] At home against Napoli on 4 October 2022, they even lost by 5 goals (1–6), Ajax's biggest defeat ever in European competition.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] After seven consecutive matches without a win, head coach Alfred Schreuder was dismissed.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] John Heitinga succeeded Schreuder as interim manager.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Under Heitinga, Ajax failed to turn things around despite a good start, with seven wins in a row.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax finished third in the Eredivisie, behind champions Feyenoord and runners-up PSV.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] This was the club's lowest ranking since the 2008/09 season, in which it also finished third.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] After the winter break, Ajax was eliminated in the first knockout phase of the Europa League by Union Berlin (3–1).
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax did reach the final of the KNVB Cup, but lost to PSV on penalties (3–2).
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] On 19 May 2023, Sven Mislintat took over as Ajax's sports director.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] He succeeded Marc Overmars, who left in early 2022.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Mislintat appointed Maurice Steijn as head coach.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Mislintat spent approximately 111 million euros on transfers.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax had its worst start to the season in fifty-nine years.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] On 29 October 2023, Ajax reached a historic low.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] This put Ajax in last place, 18th place in the Eredivisie, for the first time since the club was founded.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The position of director Mislintat became an embarrassment after it emerged that he had arranged a transfer through a player agent who was an investor in his company.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] In the evening of 24 September, Mislintat was fired with immediate effect; among other things, a lack of broad support within the club was one of the reasons.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] A day after the loss against PSV, it was announced that John van 't Schip would become the head coach until the end of the season.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Under the leadership of Van 't Schip, Ajax managed to climb to fifth place in the Eredivisie.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] In the Europa League, Ajax finished third, which meant a place in the next season's Conference League, where it eventually lost to Aston Villa in the round of 16.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] In the cup, Ajax was eliminated 3–2 by the third division amateurs of USV Hercules.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] In the summer of 2024, a rebuild began, with a new board of directors and Alex Kroes and Marijn Beuker as Technical Director and Director of Football.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] They hired Francesco Farioli as new head coach, the first foreign coach since 1998.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Under his leadership, Ajax reached the league phase of the Europa League, where it finished eleventh.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] On 9 February 2025, Ajax finished the weekend on the first place for the first time since November 2022.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax would end the season second to PSV, despite being nine points clear of their rivals with five matches to go.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Due to the late collapse that cost them the title and escalating tensions over transfers, tactics and finances, Farioli decided to leave Ajax on 19 May 2025.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The club is also particularly famous for its renowned youth programme that has produced many Dutch talents over the years.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax also regularly supplies the Dutch national youth teams with local players.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax has also expanded its talent searching programme to South Africa with Ajax Cape Town.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax Cape Town was set up with the help of Rob Moore.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax has also had a satellite club in the United States under the name Ajax America, until it filed for bankruptcy.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] There are some youth players from Ajax Cape Town that have been drafted into the Eredivisie squad, such as South African internationals Steven Pienaar and Thulani Serero and Cameroonian international Eyong Enoh.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] In 2011, Ajax opened its first youth academies outside the Netherlands when the club partnered with George Kazianis and All Star Consultancy in Greece to open the Ajax Hellas Youth Academy.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The offices are based in Nea Smyrni, Attica, with the main training facility located on the island of Corfu, hosting a total of 15 football youth academies throughout Greece and Cyprus.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Eddie van Schaik heads the organization as coach and consultant, introducing the Ajax football philosophy at the various football training camps of the country.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] In 2016, Ajax launched the ACA (Ajax Coaching Academy) with the intention of sharing knowledge, and setting up a variety of camps and clinics for both players and coaches.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax's first stadium was built in 1911 out of wood and was called Het Houten Stadion (English: The Wooden Stadium).
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax later also played in the Olympic Stadium built for the 1928 Summer Olympics hosted in Amsterdam.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] This stadium, designed by Jan Wils, is known in Dutch as *het Olympisch Stadion*.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] In 1934, Ajax moved to De Meer Stadion in east Amsterdam, close to the location of Het Houten Stadion.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] It was designed by architect and Ajax-member Daan Roodenburgh, who had also designed the club's first stadium.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] It could accommodate 29,500 spectators and Ajax continued to play there until 1996.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] For notable European and national fixtures, the club would often play at the Olympic Stadium, which could accommodate about twice the number of spectators.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] In 1996, Ajax moved to a new home ground in the southeast part of the city known as the Amsterdam Arena, since 2018 known as the Johan Cruyff Arena.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] This stadium was built by the Amsterdam city authority at a cost of $134 million.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The stadium is capable of holding 55,865 spectators.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The Arena has a retractable roof and set a trend for other modern stadiums built in Europe in the following years.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] In the Netherlands, the Arena earned a reputation for a terrible grass pitch caused by the removable roof that, even when open, takes away too much sunlight and fresh air.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] During the 2008–09 season, ground staff introduced an artificial lighting system that finally reduced this problem considerably.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The much-loved former stadium, De Meer Stadion, was torn down in 1996 and the land was sold to the city council.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] A residential neighbourhood now occupies the area.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The only thing left of the old stadium are the letters "AJAX", which nowadays is in place on the façade of the entrance at the Johan Cruyff Arena.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] A replica of the same letters are at De Toekomst, near the Johan Cruyff Arena.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] In 1900, when the club was founded, the emblem of Ajax was just a picture of an Ajax player.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The crest was slightly altered following the club's promotion to the top division in 1911 to match the club's new outfits.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] In 1928, the club logo was introduced with the head of the Greek hero Ajax.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The logo was once again changed in 1990 into an abstract version of the previous one.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The new logo still sports the portrait of Ajax, but drawn with just 11 lines, symbolizing the 11 players of a football team.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] On 17 November 2024, Ajax announced on its official website that they would revert to the classic logo of 1928 from the 2025–26 season onward, making a comeback after 34 years.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax originally played in an all-black strip with a red sash tied around the players' waists, but that strip was soon replaced by a red/white striped shirt and black shorts.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Red, black and white are the three colours of the flag of Amsterdam.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Under manager Jack Kirwan, however, the club earned promotion to the top flight of Dutch football for the first time in 1911 (then the *Eerste Klasse* or 'First Class', later named the Eredivisie), Ajax was forced to change its colours because Sparta Rotterdam already had exactly the same outfit.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Special kits for away fixtures did not exist at the time and according to football association regulations the newcomers had to change their colours if two teams in the same league had identical uniforms.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax opted for white shorts and white shirt with a broad, vertical red stripe over chest and back, which remains their colours in the present day.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] AFC Ajax is the only Dutch club with an initial public offering (IPO).
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The club is registered as a Naamloze vennootschap (N.V.) listed on the stock exchange Euronext Amsterdam, since 17 May 1998.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] With a launch price of ƒ25,- (Guilders) the club managed to a bring its total revenue up to €54 million (converted) in its first year on the market.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] After short-lived success, however, the rate dropped, at one point as low as €3.50.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Criticism was brought forth that the legal grid for a naamloze vennootschap would not be suitable for a Football club, and that the sports related ambitions would suffer from the new commercial interests of the now listed Ajax.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Shares of the company in the year 2008 were valued at approximately €5.90 per share.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] In 2008, a Commission under guidance of honorary member Uri Coronel concluded that the IPO was of no value to the club, and that measures should be taken to exit the stock exchange by purchasing back all public shares.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax's shirts have been sponsored by TDK from 1982 to 1991, and by ABN AMRO from 1991 to 2008.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] AEGON then replaced ABN AMRO as the new head sponsor for a period of seven years.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] On 1 April 2007, Ajax wore a different sponsor for the match against Heracles Almelo, *Florius*.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Florius is a banking programme launched by ABN AMRO who wanted it to be the shirt sponsor for one match.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] At the conclusion of the 2013–14 season, Ajax won the Football shirt of the Year award for its black and rose colored away shirt by Adidas.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The annual award was presented by Subside Sports, which had previously given the award to Internazionale, Juventus and the Belgium national team.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] It was Ajax's first time winning the award.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] On 7 November 2014, it was announced that Ajax had agreed to a four-and-a-half-year contract worth €8 million annually with Dutch cable operating company Ziggo as the new shirt sponsor for the club.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Having extended its contract with AEGON for half a season until December, the club featured *Fonds Gehandicaptensport*, a charitable fund for handicapped sports on its away shirts for a six-month period before transitioning to Ziggo in 2015.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Jong Ajax (*formerly more commonly known as Ajax 2*) is the reserve team of AFC Ajax.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The team is composed mostly of professional footballers, who are often recent graduates from the highest youth level (Ajax A1) serving their first professional contract as a reserve, or players who are otherwise unable to play in the first team.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Since 1992, Jong Ajax has competed in the Beloften Eredivisie, competing against other reserve teams such as Jong PSV, Jong Groningen or Jong AZ.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] They have won the Beloften Eredivisie title a record eight times, as well as the KNVB Reserve Cup three times, making them the most successful reserve squad in the Netherlands.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] By winning the Beloften Eredivisie title, Jong Ajax was able to qualify for the actual KNVB Cup, even advancing to the semi-finals on three occasions.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Its best result in the Dutch Cup was under manager Jan Olde Riekerink in 2001–02, when a semi-final loss to Utrecht in a Penalty shoot-out after extra time, which saw Utrecht advance, and thus preventing an Ajax–Jong Ajax Dutch Cup final.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The 2013–14 season marked the Jupiler League debut of the Ajax reserves' squad, Jong Ajax.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Previously playing in the Beloften Eredivisie (a separate league for reserve teams, not included in the Dutch professional or amateur league structure), players were allowed to move around freely between the reserve team and the first team during the season.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] This is no longer the case as Jong Ajax now registers and fields a separate squad from that of Ajax first team for the Eerste Divisie, the second tier of professional football in the Netherlands.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Its home matches are played at Sportpark De Toekomst, except for the occasional match in the Johan Cruyff Arena.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Furthermore, the team is not eligible for promotion to the Eredivisie or to participate in the KNVB Cup.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Jong Ajax was joined in the Eerste Divisie by Jong Twente and Jong PSV, reserve teams who have also moved from the Beloften Eredivisie to the Eerste Divisie, in place of VV Katwijk, SC Veendam and AGOVV Apeldoorn, increasing the total number of teams in the Jupiler League from 18 to 20.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax reserve squad Jong Ajax left the Beloften Eredivisie in 2013, having held a 21-year tenure in the reserves league, having also won the league title a record eight times (1994, 1996, 1998, 2001, 2002, 2004, 2005, 2009).
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax Vrouwen (*English: Ajax Women*) is the women's team of Ajax, competing in the women's eredivisie, the highest level of women's football in the Netherlands.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Founded on 18 May 2012, the women's team saw Ajax attracting many of the Netherlands top talents, with International players such as Anouk Hoogendijk, Daphne Koster and Petra Hogewoning joining the Amsterdam club in its maiden season in women's professional football.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The team won its first piece of silverware when they defeated PSV/FC Eindhoven 2–1 in the final of the KNVB Women's Cup.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax Amateurs, better known as **Ajax Zaterdag**, is a Dutch amateur football club founded 18 March 1900.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] It is the amateur team of the professional club AFC Ajax, playing its home matches at the Sportpark De Toekomst training grounds to a capacity of 5,000.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The team was promoted from the Eerste Klasse to the Hoofdklasse ahead of the 2011–12 season, the league in which it is currently competing.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The team has won the Eerste Klasse title twice, as well as the *KNVB District Cup West I on two occasions as well.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Furthermore, Ajax Zaterdag has also managed to qualify for the KNVB Cup on its own accord on three occasions, namely in 2004, 2005, 2008 and 2021.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] They even advanced to the second round, before bowing out to Vitesse on 24 September 2008.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax HVA (1922–1972) was the baseball team of Ajax founded in 1922, and competed as founding members of the Honkbal Hoofdklasse, the top flight of professional baseball in the Netherlands.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax won the national baseball title a total of four times (1924, 1928, 1942, 1948) before the club opted to no longer field a baseball team, and to focus solely on football in 1972.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax spent a total of 50 years at the top flight of Baseball in the Netherlands from 1922 to 1972.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The dissolution of Ajax baseball club resulted in the players finding a new sponsor in a mustard manufacturing company called Luycks, while merging with the Diemen Giants to become the Luycks Giants, thus replacing both former clubs.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] In 2016, Ajax launched an esports team, with Koen Weijland as the club's first signing, making its debut on the Global stage of professional gaming.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] They have since signed the likes of Dani Hagebeuk, Lev Vinken, Joey Calabro and Bob van Uden, the latter spent his first season on loan to the esports team of Japanese club Sagan Tosu.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Feyenoord from Rotterdam is Ajax's archrival.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Every year both clubs play the *De Klassieker* ("The Classic"), a match between the teams from the two largest cities of the Netherlands.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Till the 1973/74-season, Ajax and Feyenoord were the only two clubs in the Netherlands who were able to clinch national titles, as well as achieve continental and even global success.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] From the 1974/75-season on, PSV (Eindhoven) and AZ (Alkmaar) too, competed with Ajax and Feyenoord.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] A meeting between the two clubs became the measure for who was truly the best club in the Netherlands.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The *Klassieker* is the most famous of all the rivalries in the Netherlands and the matches are always sold out.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The fixture is seen in the public eye as "the graceful and elegant football of Ajax, against the indomitable fighting spirit of Feyenoord"; the confidence of the capital city versus the blue collar mentality of Rotterdam.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Matches are known for their tension and violence, both on and off the pitch.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Over the years, several violent incidents have taken place involving rival supporters, leading to the current prohibition of away supporters in both stadiums.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The lowest point was reached on 23 March 1997, when supporters of both clubs met on a field near Beverwijk, where Ajax-supporter Carlo Picornie was fatally injured, the incident is commonly referred to as the "Battle of Beverwijk".
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] PSV is also a rival of Ajax, but in terms of tension and rivalry, these matches are not as loaded as the duels with Feyenoord.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The rivalry has existed for some time with PSV and stems from various causes, such as the different interpretations of whether current national and international successes of both clubs correlates and the supposed opposition between the Randstad and the province.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The matches between these two teams is commonly referred to as "De Topper" ("The Topper"), and involves the two most trophy-laden sides in Dutch football and is essentially a clash of two competing schools of thought in Dutch football.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Historically, PSV compete with a workmanlike ethic, preferring a more robust 4–3–1–2 or 4–2–3–1, typically shunning the frivolous 4–3–3 approach favoured in Amsterdam.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] While Rinus Michels and Johan Cruyff helped to innovate Total Football in the sixties and seventies, a different philosophy was honed in Eindhoven by Kees Rijvers and Guus Hiddink in the late 1970s and '80s.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] This in turn has created one of the more philosophical rivalries in football, an ideological battleground, which is gradually becoming as heated and intense as the matches Ajax and Feyenoord partake in.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] A more recent rivalry has developed with AZ from nearby Alkmaar.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Since both Ajax and AZ are situated in North Holland province, the fixture is often referred to as "De Noord-Hollandse derby" ("The North Holland derby").
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Although the clubs first met in the 1960s, the rivalry intensified when AZ won the Dutch championship in 2009.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The derby has since become a key clash in the Dutch football season, often with high stakes and impact on the league.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Although many Ajax supporters regard AZ as their "little brother", it remains a competitive and emotionally charged fixture.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The supporters have clashed several times since 2009.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] In December 2024, for example, Ajax supporters attacked an AZ pub in Alkmaar during a derby match.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] A notable incident occurred on 21 December 2011 during a KNVB Cup match.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] An Ajax supporter ran onto the pitch and attacked AZ goalkeeper Esteban Alvarado, who defended himself by kicking the pitch invader twice and received a straight red card from referee Bas Nijhuis.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] AZ coach Gertjan Verbeek took his players off the pitch in protest, following which the match was definitively abandoned.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The sides furthermore compete for staff and youth prospects in the North Holland region.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] When technical director Martin van Geel left AZ for Ajax in 2006, AZ director Dirk Scheringa banned him from the club's stadium.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax have several other rivalries, although in most cases the sentiment is mostly felt by the opposition and is more directed towards Ajax, with one of them being Utrecht.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Although the rivalry is more felt on the Utrecht side than with Ajax, matchups between the two sides are often quite intense.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Both teams have fanatic supporters, and clashes off the pitch are more often the rule than the exception.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The same goes for ADO Den Haag, with both supporter groups often getting in conflicts, when ADO-Hooligans set fire to the supporters home of Ajax, and Ajax hooligans subsequently broke into the supporters home of ADO, tensions between the two clubs rose.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] In 2006, supporters from both clubs were banned from attending away matches for five years due to frequent violent outbreaks and clashes.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Further teams who share a rivalry with Ajax include Twente, Vitesse and Groningen.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Past rivalries include local Amsterdam derbies between Ajax and clubs such as Blauw-Wit, DWS and De Volewijckers (which later merged to become FC Amsterdam in 1972).
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] However, the tension between the local sides lessened as the division of the clubs through playing in different leagues over time became greater.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Years of not competing in the same league resulted in less frequent match-ups, until tensions finally settled between the Amsterdam clubs.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The last Amsterdam derby to take place in an official league match was when Ajax defeated FC Amsterdam 5–1 on 19 March 1978.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax is known for having fanatic core supporter-groups, of which F-Side and VAK410 are the most famous.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The F-Side was founded on 3 October 1976, and is situated right behind the goal in the Johan Cruyff Arena, on the southern end of the stadium in rows 125–129.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Its name is derived from the group's former location on the F-side of the old De Meer Stadion.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The F-side supporters are responsible for a big part of the atmosphere in the stadium, and are also known for rioting during and after matches.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] If in any match Ajax should win the coin toss, the second half of the match Ajax always play towards the south-end of the stadium.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] VAK410 (English: Row 410) was founded in 2001 and is situated in the Zuidhoek (*South corner*) of the stadium on the upper ring in rows 424–425.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The group was originally situated on the North-West side of the stadium in row 410, from where it derives its name, until relocating to their current place in the stands in 2008.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Members of VAK410 are known to perform various stunts, which include massive banners, to enhance the atmosphere in the stadium.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Neither F-Side or VAK410 have seats in their sections of the stadium, and both groups stand for the duration of the match.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Through the official *Football Top 20* of Dutch sports research group *SPORT+MARKT*, it was revealed in 2010 that Ajax had approximately 7.1 million supporters throughout Europe.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] This is significantly more than rivals Feyenoord and PSV (each 1.6 and 1.3 million, respectively), which puts Ajax as the club with the 15th-most supporters across Europe.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The study also revealed that approximately 39% of the Netherlands were Ajax supporters.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] It is noteworthy that not all stadiums share the capacity of the Johan Cruyff Arena.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The Supporters Club Ajax (Dutch: *Supportersvereniging Ajax*) is officially the largest supporters club in the Netherlands with 94,000 members.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Founded on 7 May 1992, the supporters club organize big monthly events throughout the Netherlands, and particularly around the official Ajax Open Training Day, which attracts thousands of supporters each year.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Furthermore, the supporters group is responsible for the Ajax Life website, as well as the fanzine which is issued 20 times a year.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] In 2006, the AFCA Supportersclub was introduced as the club's second official supporters' association, through the merger of the Onafhankelijke Fanclub Ajax (OFA) and the Ajax Supporters Delegatie (ASD).
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The AFCA Supportersclub has a reported 42,000 members, as well as a former member on the Board of Administration of Ajax, in Ronald Pieloor.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The third official supporters club is the Ajax Business Associates (ABA).
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Founded in 1991 the ABA is the Business club of Ajax.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Members occupy the skyboxes in the Stadium and can make use of the clubs' amenities and luxury suites including the ABA club and lounge.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The ABA is also responsible for hosting the annual Ajax Business Golf Trophy, an amateur golf tournament where several active and former Ajax players, as well as prominent people and members of the ABA, participate.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] This graph displays the average attendance for home matches of Ajax from 1988 to 2018, whereby the difference in capacity of the De Meer Stadion and the Johan Cruyff Arena (opened in 1996) is clearly visible.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Historically, Ajax was popularly seen as having "Jewish roots".
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The city of Amsterdam was historically referred to as a Mokum city, Mokum (מקום) being the Yiddish word for "place" or "safe haven", though 75% of the Jewish citizens were killed during the Holocaust.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] This Jewish imagery eventually became a central part of Ajax fans' culture.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] At one point, ringtones of "Hava Nagila", a Hebrew folk song, could be downloaded from the club's official website.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Beginning in the 1980s, fans of Ajax's rivals escalated their antisemitic rhetoric, chanting slogans like "Hamas, Hamas/Jews to the gas" ("Hamas, hamas, joden aan het gas"), hissing to imitate the flow of gas, giving Nazi salutes, and other things.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The eventual result was that many genuinely Jewish Ajax fans stopped going to games.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] In the 2000s, the club began trying to persuade fans to drop its Jewish image.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] In 2013, a documentary titled *Superjews* was released by NTR and Viewpoint Productions which premiered at the International Documentary Film Festival Amsterdam (IDFA).
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] The film was directed by Nirit Peled, an Israeli living in Amsterdam, and an independent film maker who offers a very personal view into the game, the lore of Ajax and its relation to Judaism from both the supporters as well as from a Jewish perspective.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Before and after a UEFA Europa League game between Israeli team Maccabi Tel Aviv and Ajax on 7 November 2024 in the Johan Cruyff Arena, tensions surrounding the Gaza war erupted into violence.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Note: Flags indicate national team as defined under FIFA eligibility rules; some limited exceptions apply.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p01] Players may hold more than one non-FIFA nationality.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] Ajax also won in 1972, however UEFA only sanctioned the UEFA Super Cup for the first time in 1973 so the 1972 edition was an unofficial one.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] Played against Rangers, winners of the 1971–72 European Cup Winners' Cup, it went ahead as 'a celebration of the Centenary of Rangers F.C.' (see below) because Rangers was serving a one-year ban at the time, imposed by UEFA for the misbehaviour of its fans.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] That victory meant Ajax had won every tournament (5 in total) they entered that year, a feat Celtic achieved in 1967 (with 6 trophies), Barcelona in 2009 (6 trophies), and Bayern in 2020 (also 6 trophies).
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] Ajax have won numerous friendly tournaments, unsanctioned by UEFA or FIFA, including the Amsterdam Tournament, Bruges Matins Trophy, Trofeo Santiago Bernabéu, Eusébio Cup, Ted Bates Trophy, Jalkapalloturnaus and Chippie Polar Cup (*for a complete list, see: list of AFC Ajax honours*).
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] Ajax have a total of 50 honorary club members, from people who have been invested within the club's administrative engagements, to committed players who have excelled in the athletic department.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] Nine members still remain, including Louis van Gaal.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] Below is a table with Ajax's domestic results since the introduction of the Eredivisie in 1956.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] The Club van 100 is the official list of football players who have appeared in one hundred or more official matches for AFC Ajax.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] The club currently has a total of over 150 members.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] The record for league appearances is held by **Mr.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] Ajax** himself Sjaak Swart, who appeared in 463 league matches for Ajax.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] There is a beneficiary team called Lucky Ajax, which was initiated by Sjaak Swart.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] Lucky Ajax participate in at least one match a year, usually in the name of charity, and commonly at football ceremonies to bid farewell to retiring players.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] One of the prerequisites for playing on Lucky Ajax, which is invitational only, is that you are a member of the Club van 100, having made at least 100 official match appearances for Ajax in the first team of the club.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] Lucky Ajax is a beneficiary team that was initiated by Sjaak Swart in the seventies, competing in at least one match a year, usually in the name of charity and/or to bid farewell to retiring former Ajax players.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] The team is made up of various members of the Club van 100 of Ajax who will come out of retirement for this match to face the Ajax squad that is current of that year.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] Past participants have included Barry Hulshoff, Sonny Silooy, Simon Tahamata, Ronald Koeman, Tscheu La Ling, Gerrie Mühren, John van 't Schip, Brian Roy, Stanley Menzo, Peter van Vossen and Fred Grim.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] The name Lucky Ajax is derived from the famous "Lucky Ajax" nickname from how people used to refer to the club when Ajax would either win a match by chance, by a decision of a referee, or by coincidence such as was said to be the case during the infamous *Mistwedstrijd* ("Fog Match").
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] As of the 2007–08 season, no player could wear the number 14 shirt at Ajax after the club decided to retire the shirt out of respect for Johan Cruyff, "the legendary number fourteen".
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] Cruyff himself laughed off the tribute, saying the club had to let its best player play with number 14.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] Spanish midfielder Roger was the last player to wear the number.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] Marvin Zeegelaar wore the shirt number in preparation for the 2011–12 season in one preseason match, while Aras Özbiliz wore the number 14 shirt in one pre-season match ahead of the 2011–12 season as well.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] The club stated that this was, in fact, not done in error.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] Below is a list of all players to wear the number 14 shirt since Johan Cruyff's departure.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] Established in 1975 as the Amsterdam 700 Tournament to celebrate 700 years of history in the city.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] The tournament was hosted annually each summer by Ajax until 1992, when the last edition of the original tournament was played.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] It returned in 1999 with the backing of the International Event Partnership (IEP).
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] Four teams participated in the competition, played in a league format since 1986.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] Since its return, the tournament used an unusual point scoring system.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] As with most league competitions, three points were awarded for a win, one for a draw, and none for a loss.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] An additional point, however, was awarded for each goal scored.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] The system was designed to reward teams that adopted a more attacking style of play.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] Each entrant played two matches, with the winner being the club that finished at the top of the table.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] The original competition was held at Het Olympisch Stadion where Ajax played the bigget games until 1996.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] The Amsterdam Arena (now Johan Cruyff Arena) played host to the event since its return until the last edition was played in 2009.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] Ajax is the most successful team of the tournament, having won it a record ten times, while Benfica from Portugal was the last team to win the tournament, in 2009.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] Each Summer the city of Amsterdam and Ajax invite U-19 teams from various top clubs from around the World to participate in the tournament.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] Seven teams are invited and play in the competition every year.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] Over the years, clubs such as Barcelona, Juventus, Chelsea and Real Madrid have had their senior youth teams participate in the tournament.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] Cruzeiro from Brazil is the most successful club in the history of the tournament, having won it three times in total.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] Established in 2010, the AEGON Future Cup is an international friendly tournament for Under-17 youth teams, which is organized by AFC Ajax and their main sponsor, the insurance company AEGON.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] The tournament is held each year at the Johan Cruyff Arena and at the Sportpark De Toekomst, the team's training ground, which also inspired the name of the competition, since *De Toekomst* in Dutch means The Future.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] Every year during the Easter weekend, six U-17 teams are invited to participate in the competition, while the seventh place for the contesters is reserved for the winners of the "Craques Mongeral AEGON Future Cup" in Brazil, the sister competition of the tournament in South America.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] Youth teams from top clubs such as Manchester United, Bayern Munich, Milan and many more have participated in the competition over the years.
[src:abn-amro/afc-ajax-p02] Ajax is the most successful club of the tournament, having won the trophy a total of five times.
[src:abn-amro/amro-bank] The **Amsterdamsche en Rotterdamsche Bank** (**AMRO Bank**, lit.
[src:abn-amro/amro-bank] 'Bank of Amsterdam and Rotterdam') was a major Dutch bank that was created in 1964 by the merger of the Amsterdamsche Bank (est.
[src:abn-amro/amro-bank] In 1991, it merged with Algemene Bank Nederland (ABN) to form ABN AMRO.
[src:abn-amro/amro-bank] As early as 1939, there had been plans to merge the two banks but the banks shelved these plans in anticipation of Dutch involvement in World War II.
[src:abn-amro/amro-bank] The two banks announced their merger on 11 June 1964, and were integrated during the following year.
[src:abn-amro/amro-bank] As soon as the AMRO Bank was set up, it set about gaining market share in business lending, leasing and factoring as well as in medium to long term credit.
[src:abn-amro/amro-bank] To do this it established the *Nationale Bank voor Middellang Krediet* business unit to provide medium to long term credit.
[src:abn-amro/amro-bank] It established or acquired companies such as *Mahuko* (Society for leasing) and *Amstel Lease* for its leasing business.
[src:abn-amro/amro-bank] The financing of factoring was brought together under the *International Factors Nederland B.V.*, the oldest factoring company in the Netherlands.
[src:abn-amro/amro-bank] In the 1960s and 1970s, like many other banking companies, AMRO saw growth in retail banking and this became a much bigger part of the business.
[src:abn-amro/amro-bank] Its wholesale banking was also strengthened by the acquisition of Pierson, Heldring & Pierson (PHP) in 1975.
[src:abn-amro/amro-bank] AMRO operated PHP as an independent unit under its existing name.
[src:abn-amro/amro-bank] Another acquisition was Utrecht based *Bank Flaors & Ko*, which had been in existence since 1691.
[src:abn-amro/amro-bank] This bank was absorbed under the AMRO Bank brand.
[src:abn-amro/amro-bank] In 1967, AMRO Bank was one of the founders of the consortium bank *Banque Européenne de Crédit à Moyen Terme* (European bank of long term credit) based in Belgium.
[src:abn-amro/amro-bank] The aim was create an entity that was large enough to work at an international level.
[src:abn-amro/amro-bank] Soon after this, with their sights on European integration, AMRO Bank announced plans to collaborate with Belgian Generale Bank with the aim of building a European international bank.
[src:abn-amro/amro-bank] However, this project was too ambitious and never managed to get off the ground.
[src:abn-amro/amro-bank] It was only when the Dutch Government announced that it was relaxing its merger rules for financial institutions that ABN and AMRO Bank were able to seize the opportunity to merge and to create a bank large enough to fulfill these ambitions.
[src:abn-amro/apg-pension-fund] APG was established on 1 March 2008 as an independent administration organization of Stichting Pensioenfonds ABP (ABP).
[src:abn-amro/apg-pension-fund] In the same year, it merged with Cordares, which carried out pension administration for bpfBOUW (The Foundation for the Construction Industry Pension Fund).
[src:abn-amro/apg-pension-fund] APG is known as the asset manager of ABP.
[src:abn-amro/apg-pension-fund] AlpInvest Partners was owned by APG and PGGM until it was sold to The Carlyle Group in 2011.
[src:abn-amro/apg-pension-fund] APG manages investments for various pension funds in the Netherlands.
[src:abn-amro/apg-pension-fund] APG has offices in Amsterdam, Heerlen, Brussels, New York, Hong Kong and Singapore.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] ASML was founded in 1984 as a joint venture between the Dutch technology companies Philips and ASM International; it became an independent publicly traded entity four years later.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] Having been established to complete development of Philips' previously in-house project to produce their own lithography machine, ASML initially had no market-ready products.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] Furthermore, ASML's first product, the PAS 2000, was a commercial and technical failure; however, the company did attain commercial success during the early 1990s with the PAS 5500.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] During 1997, ASML began studying the potential shift to EUV.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] By 2002, the company had become the largest supplier of lithography machines.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] While sales were negatively impacted by the start of the Great Recession in 2008, ASML had effectively recovered by 2011.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] In July 2012, Intel purchased a 15 percent stake in ASML in exchange for $4.1 billion; Samsung and TSMC also bought stakes in the firm under a co-investment program.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] ASML completed development of its EUV machines in the late 2010s.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] During the 2010s and 2020s, both the US and Dutch governments imposed new oversight and restrictions on each individual sale of ASML technology to China.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] ASML's corporate headquarters is in Veldhoven, just outside the city of Eindhoven in the Netherlands, and is the location for research, development, manufacturing, and assembly.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] ASML employs more than 42,000 people from 143 nationalities and relies on a network of nearly 5,000 tier 1 suppliers.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] ASML has a worldwide customer base and over 60 service points in 16 countries.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] It has offices in the Netherlands, the United States, Belgium, France, Germany, Ireland, Israel, Italy, the United Kingdom, China, Hong Kong, Japan, South Korea, Malaysia, Singapore, and Taiwan.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] The company is listed on both the Euronext Amsterdam and Nasdaq stock exchanges, as ASML.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] It is also a component of the Euro Stoxx 50 and Nasdaq-100.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] ASML can be traced back to the 1970s and the Dutch electronics company Philips.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] By the early 1980s, Philips had projected that considerable additional investment would be necessary to complete its development, but this need came at a time in which the company was trying to reduce expenditure.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] Accordingly, in 1984, the company elected to spin-off its lithography machine activities into a joint venture with another Dutch firm, ASM International, which specialised in the supply of equipment to the semiconductor industry.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] This decision shaped the machine as well, which adopted a modular design and used clearly defined subsystems.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] Early on, ASML struggled to secure business, having no market share and no brand recognition at the start of its operations.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] Furthermore, the firm's first product, the PAS 2000, was a commercial and technical failure, having used oil pressure (instead of electric motors) to move the wafer during exposure, which had a tendency to leak; future lithograph machines made by ASML would use conventional electric motors instead.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] By the start of 1988, Philips was reportedly considered shutting down the joint venture entirely after ASM International, however, sufficient support was present on Philip's board to continue with operations, giving ASML the time to develop another lithography machine, the PAS 5500.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] Accordingly, in 1988, ASML became an independent publicly traded entity; that same year, it first adopted the name ASML, which is its official name and not an abbreviation.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] In 1991, ASML released the PAS 5500, which quickly became the company's first commercial breakout.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] In contrast to the more precise contemporary lithography machines from competing firm Nikon, the modular design used by ASML meant that its machines could be fixed quickly on site, reducing downtime and making it possible to extend the machine’s operating life.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] The serviceability advantage was reportedly the key factor that led to IBM ordering the PAS 5500 over its Japanese counterparts.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] The first company to operate the PAS 5500 was Micron Technology, one of the world's largest producers of computer memory and storage; it became ASML's largest customer for a time.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] The success of the PAS 5500 line propelled ASML into a period of intense competition with both Canon and Nikon, who were the leaders of the lithography market at the time.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] In 1997, ASML began studying a shift to using extreme ultraviolet.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] Two years later, it joined a consortium, which included Intel and two other U.S. chipmakers, in order to exploit fundamental research conducted by the US Department of Energy.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] Because the Cooperative Research and Development Agreement (CRADA) it operates under is funded by the US government, licensing must be approved by Congress.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] Furthermore, in return for being permitted to join this consortium, ASML committed to the establishment of a US-based research center and to source 55 percent of components for all machines sold in the US from American suppliers.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] ASML collaborated with various manufacturers to obtain mirrors, including the Belgian firms IMEC and Sematech as well as Germany's Carl Zeiss.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] In 2001, ASML acquired the US-based lithography equipment manufacturer Silicon Valley Group (SVG) after it had encountered liquidity issues, The SVG acquisition, which has also been licensed for EUV research results, involved ASML in an arrangement to supply 193 nm scanners to Intel.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] In 2002, it became the largest supplier of photolithography systems.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] Aided by the adoption of the dual-stage TWINSCAN architecture to reduce idle time, ASML machines could produce more chips per hour than any competitor's products; this competitive edge was so strong that the company could charge higher prices for their machines and still grow its market share.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] By the end of the decade, it had secured two thirds of the global lithography market and had become the dominant supplier for the growing smartphone market.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] During December 2006, ASML announced the acquisition of rival firm BRION Technologies in exchange for $270 million; this transaction into direction competition with the major EDA vendors who had similar products - Cadence Design Systems, Synopsys, and Mentor Graphics.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] ASML had recovered by 2011, reporting record-high revenue for that year.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] During the early 2010s, ASML sharply increased its annual R&D budget, rising from just under $500 million in 2010 to $1 billion in 2015.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] While this expenditure was necessary in order to complete the development of its next generation EUV machines, financing such amounts was not straightforward.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] To achieve this, ASML launched a co-investment program in 2012, under which 23 percent of the company was sold to its three largest customers: Intel, TSMC and Samsung.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] Intel's investment into $4.1 billion into ASML, made in July 2012, gave it a 15 percent stake in the company; this move was stated to accelerate Intel's transition from 300 mm to 450 mm wafers as well as support further development of EUV lithography.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] That same month, ASML offered another 10 percent of its shares to other companies.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] Beyond simply generating additional funds, these new stakeholders were incentivised to participate in ASML's research efforts.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] TSMC in particular worked closely with ASML to develop and troubleshoot its EUV machines, being keen to use them to manufacture their own products.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] As part of their EUV strategy, ASML announced the acquisition of DUV and EUV sources manufacturer Cymer in exchange for $2.55 billion in October 2012; this transaction was completed in May 2013.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] Cymer's technology was viewed as being useful to developing ASML's EUV machines.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] In November 2013, ASML paused development of 450 mm lithography equipment, citing uncertain timing of chipmaker demand.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] In early 2015, ASML reported an instance of intellectual property theft; allegedly a number of employees had been found stealing confidential data from its Silicon Valley software subsidiary that develops software for machine optimization.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] Three years later, ASML was awarded $223 million in damages pertaining to this incident, as well as securing the offending company's own intellectual property.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] ASML employees have often been viewed as highly desirable recruitment targets for other tech companies.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] In June 2016, ASML announced their plans to acquire Taiwan-based Hermes Microvision Inc. in exchange for about $3.1 billion; it was reported that this transaction would secure technology for creating smaller and more advanced semiconductors.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] In 2018, the Trump administration tried to block the sale of ASML technology to China.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] This move, which has been viewed as part of a wider "technological cold war" between the US and China, may have contributed to the 2020–2023 global chip shortage and impacted the business opportunities available to ASML.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] In July 2020, ASML stated that it had acquired the German optical glassmaking firm Berliner Glas Group, which will help to satisfy the increasing need for components for its EUV systems; at the time of this acquisition, ASML's outstanding orders had reportedly risen to €10 billion.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] In July 2021, European Commissioner Thierry Breton, visited ASML and announced a goal of at least 20 percent of global production of semiconductors in Europe by 2030, and support via a European Alliance on semiconductors.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] After reporting earnings in July 2021, the company said they had a near monopoly for machines used by TSMC and Samsung to make the advanced chips.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] In February 2023, ASML claimed that a former worker in China "allegedly" stole information about the company's technology.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] This was not the first time that ASML was allegedly linked with an intellectual property breach connected to China.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] In its 2021 annual report, ASML mentioned that Dongfang Jingyuan Electron Limited "was actively marketing products in China that could potentially infringe on ASML's IP rights." At the time, the United States Department of Commerce expressed concern about economic espionage against ASML.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] In October 2023, Dutch newspaper NRC Handelsblad reported that the former employee who "allegedly" stole data about ASML's technology subsequently went to work for Huawei.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] In March 2023, the Dutch government placed restrictions on chip equipment exports in order to protect national security.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] This measure affected ASML as one of the most important companies in the global microchip supply chain.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] Export license requirements came into effect in September 2023.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] Three months later, the Netherlands' Institute for Human Rights ruled that despite the country's constitution prohibiting discrimination based on nationality, ASML was allowed to reject job applications from residents of countries subject to sanctions under the U.S.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] Export Administration Regulations (such as China, Cuba, Iran, North Korea, and Syria) in order to remain compliant with U.S. law.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] In January 2024, the Dutch government placed further restrictions on the shipment of some advanced chip-making equipment to China.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] On 6 September 2024, the Dutch government tightened export controls on certain ASML chipmaking equipment, aligning its policy with U.S. restrictions to limit China's access to advanced technology amid safety and geopolitical concerns.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] These restrictions were expanded for tighter export controls in January 2025, with ASML required to apply for export licenses with the Dutch government instead of the U.S.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] In December 2025, Reuters reported that China had secretly built a prototype EUV machine in Shenzhen with the assistance of former ASML engineers, with the machine expected to produce working chips between 2028 and 2030.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] ASML produces the photolithography machines used in the production of integrated circuits, called "scanners".
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] In these machines, patterns are optically imaged onto a silicon wafer that is covered with a film of light-sensitive material (photoresist).
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] This procedure is repeated dozens of times on a single wafer.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] The photoresist is then further processed to create the actual electronic circuits on the silicon.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] The optical imaging that ASML's machines deal with is used in the fabrication of nearly all integrated circuits.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] As of 2025, ASML had 83% percent of the worldwide sales of lithography machines.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] ASML's earlier competition consisted of Ultratech, Canon, Nikon, MKS Instruments, Lam Research and Cadence Design Systems.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] Since immersion lithography was first proposed by Burn-Jeng Lin in the 1970s, ASML cooperated with TSMC.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] In 2004, TSMC began commercial production of 90 nanometer semiconductor nodes using ASML immersion lithography.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] By 2011, their high-end TWINSCAN NXT:1950i system was used for producing features down to 32 nanometres at up to 200 wafers per hour, using a water immersion lens and an argon fluoride laser that produces light at a wavelength of 193 nm.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] By 2011, an average lithography machine cost €27 million.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] Deep ultraviolet lithography (DUV) devices from ASML use ultraviolet light to print the tiny features that form the microchip's structure.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] Extreme ultraviolet lithography (EUV) is a critical technology used to create the smallest and most complex chip designs.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] ASML holds a near-monopoly in the EUV market.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] The company's machines are capable of etching patterns as small as 8 nanometers, 1/10000 the width of a human hair.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] EUV machines produce light in the 13.5 nm wavelength range by focusing a high-energy laser on microscopic droplets of molten tin to produce a plasma, which then emits EUV light.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] The light is bounced off Zeiss mirrors onto the surface of a silicon wafer to form the designs for the chip.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] In 2009, the IMEC research center in Belgium produced the world's first functional 22 nm CMOS Static random-access memory memory cells with a prototype EUV lithography machine.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] After decades of development, ASML shipped the first production EUV machine in either 2011 or 2013.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] As of 2022, ASML has shipped around 140 EUV systems.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] ASML's best-selling EUV product has been the TWINSCAN NXE:3600D, which costs up to $200 million.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] The machine weighs 180 tons and needs three Boeing 747s to transport.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] ASML is working on the next generation of EUV systems, with the first shipments for R&D shipped to Intel in December 2023, and TSMC in late 2024.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] The platform is designated *High-NA* as it increases the numerical aperture (NA) from 0.33 to 0.55. each system costs approximately $370 million.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] ASML became a sponsor of the PSV football club in 2019 together with Philips, VDL Groep, Royal Swinkels Family Brewers and Jumbo Supermarkets from the Brainport region.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] Together they run various initiatives like soccer training camps for school children, the development of interactive programs for teaching, assisting community members in need or who are new to the region, as well as supporting a vitality program that is online.
[src:abn-amro/asml-holding] ASML was the title partner of the Eindhoven marathon from 2022 - 2024.
